Month = {MAR-APR},
Abstract = {Expected selection response (R) is widely used in plant breeding to
   compare populations and selection schemes, but methods have not been
   described for estimating variances or confidence intervals of R, or, if
   they have, their validity is uncertain. In this paper, we describe an
   exact and approximate standard error of R and normal-approximation
   intervals of R. We used simulation to test the validity of these
   intervals by comparing realized coverage probabilities to stated
   coverage probabilities for different experiment sizes, stated coverage
   probability values, and values of family-mean heritability (H).
   Coverages of the normal-approximation interval estimated using the exact
   standard error (interval R1) ranged from 0.874 to 0.922 and 0.932 to
   0.966 for stated coverages of 0.90 and 0.95, respectively. Coverages of
   the normal-approximation interval estimated using the approximate
   standard error (interval R2) ranged from 0.880 to 0.940 and 0.934 to
   0.980 for stated coverages of 0.90 and 0.95, respectively. Both R1 and
   R2 are valid interval estimators for R if the usual assumptions of the
   analysis of variance are met.},
