Pages = {1-23},
Note = {2nd International Symposium on Systems Approaches for Agricultural
   Development - Applications of Systems Approaches at the Field Level, INT
   RICE RES INST, LOS BANOS, PHILIPPINES, DEC 06-08, 1995},
Organization = {Int Rice Res Inst; Int Consortium Agr Syst Applicat; Simulat \& Syst
   Anal Rice Prod Project},
Abstract = {Plant breeders face enormous challenges in the coming decades to greatly
   increase food production with less land and higher input use efficiency,
   Crop breeding has to be more knowledge-intensive and should integrate
   information from related disciplines to achieve this goal. Systems
   tools, such as crop simulation models, data bases, geographical
   information systems (GIS), and optimization and risk analysis
   techniques, facilitate integration of the effects of climatic, edaphic,
   management, biotic and socioeconomic factors on crop growth,
   productivity, and profitability. These tools provide us with an
   opportunity to accelerate the use of interdisciplinary knowledge in crop
   breeding. They are useful for evaluating hypotheses and setting breeding
   goals for different physiological traits in various agroenvironments,
   using historical weather data and techniques of risk analysis.
   Physiologically sound models may also assist in extrapolating the
   performance of a crop population from one site to another, in reducing
   the number of locations in varietal evaluation programmes, and in
   describing why a particular variety does not perform well in all
   locations. They can also play a significant role in determining
   strategies for minimizing damage to germplasm caused by various pests in
   different regions. Alternatively, simulation models can assess the
   relative performance of plant types in scenarios involving various
   levels of pest infestations in different agroecosystems. In this paper,
   we discuss the expectations of plant breeders from crop physiology and
   modelling and explore the opportunities offered by the systems approach,
   review some case studies, assess limitations on the use of models in
   breeding, and finally comment on future needs.},
